Do you modify your skincare routine at all in the winter??
The cold dry weather in the winter months can be super irritating to the skin. The best thing you can do is cut back frequency of use of products with acids and retinoids. So maybe that means you use those products 3x/week or every other day instead of daily.

You can also use aquaphor on your face at night as the last step in your routine after moisturizer to lock in hydration. Just be sure to skip your retinoid that night bc it can intensify it😉
Might have overdone it this year🤣 But gotta start somewhere!

If you’re frustrated that you keep noticing dark spots on your face…don’t be! We are constantly getting sun exposure and so just like treating acne, treating pigmentation isn’t something you ever stop doing. It can definitely be managed just not cured. If you notice the surface of my skin has very little pigment, that’s because of high quality skincare keeping visible pigment minimized but I am use twice daily skincare to repair, correct, and protect. 

If I stopped doing my skincare routine or started getting a lot more sun exposure the dark spots would go wild. Pigmentation and yes even a tan is our body’s response to protect itself. It means dna damage has been done and now it’s using it resources to.

Why is it important to have both an AM and PM skincare routine?! 🗓

Well, the most simple way to explain it is:
 ☀️morning skincare routine is about = protection 
🌛evening routine is about = repair + correction

Essential products for the morning routine are:

→ vitamin C
→ SPF

Think of it as your skin is running a marathon, these products help fuel and shield the skin from damaging stressors you encounter throughout the day. 🏃‍♀️🍅 (watch the video, the emojis will make sense.)

The key products for your nighttime routine are:

→ a retinoid
→ antioxidants

Retinoids, like @barefaced RetinAL Skin Therapy, enhance and accelerate what your skin is already doing naturally at night! 🔄 Typically, the peak regeneration window is between 11pm-1am. This is why we advocate for a full 8 hours of sleep—it really is “beauty” rest for skin cells.

As for vitamin C, your skin has to run a marathon again the next day, so just like you would need electrolytes to recover, your skin is craving antioxidants to recover as well.

Online, unbacked trends may seem like all the rage, but listen to @jordanharper_np’s mom 🗣️ if something seems too good to be true then it probably is. And that defintiley applies skincare as well.

Skincare School analogy time:

Cars have been around for 100+ years. 🚙 And while cars are much more advanced than they were back in Henry Ford’s day, if you break them down bare bones structurally, they aren’t that different. They still have 4 wheels, a frame, doors, windows, etc. 

It’s the same for skincare. 🧖‍♀️ Wonderful, new, and innovative advancements are continually being made, but structurally, skincare always comes back to the same tried-and-true, foundational principles in order to be effective in the long run.🏃‍♀️ 

And just like you’re not going anywhere if you don’t have 4 🛞 on your car, your skin isn’t going to make any progress if you’re not using the 4 core products—the essentials to long-term healthy skin across all skin types…

1️⃣An SPF — to prevent + protect —always easier than correction

2️⃣A retinoid — to repair + correct — the best retinoid is the one you can consistently tolerate 5-7 nights/week

3️⃣An antioxidant — to prevent + repair — vitamin c is the main one
 
4️⃣An exfoliant — to correct + prevent —for removing dead skin cells from the surface of the skin, which prevents buildup + future breakouts, plus helps your other skincare products work more effectively.

Hold these tires together with cleansing 🧼 and moisturizer🧴to keep your car…we mean skin barrier…in tact!

This is the foundation. From here, you can make your “car” as fancy as you want and use targeted skincare and treatments to address your unique skin type and concerns, like dark spots, dryness, or breakouts.

Are you using these core 4 products?! Comment Y/N below!

Sooo tell me…how many nights a week are you using a retinoid?! 🤔

Outside of sunscreen, retinoids are hands-down the single best anti-aging topical product you can use! But, to reap the benefits, clinical data shows you need to be using a retinoid consistently. Like, 5-7x/week consistently.

If you haven’t reached that goal yet (thanks to increased dryness, redness, sensitivity, or irritation when you first start a retinoid) then try this: 

The Rule of 3’ — 

Month 1️⃣ — use your retinoid every 3rd night

Month 2️⃣ — use your retinoid every 2nd night

Month 3️⃣ — use your retinoid every night, or on alternating nights.

We love RetinAL Skin Therapy because while it’s an estimated 20x stronger than retinol, it’s much better tolerated than prescription-strength retinoic acid. It hits right in the sweet spot peak potency and frequency. 🤌👩‍🍳😘

Yes, retinoids do thin the stratum corneum, which is the outermost layer of dead 💀🪦skin cells. BUT who cares about dead skin. We care about the dermis (the middle and thickest layer of the skin) and retinoids thicken and strengthen the dermis by stimulating collagen production🧬🙌🏼⚡️
the more you know✍🏼 the best retinoid is the one your skin can tolerate consistently and that means 5-7 nights/week😉

Looking for best way to treat dark circles? 🌒👀

You’re not alone! Dark circles can be from a variety of factors, like:

🧬 Genetics
🤧 Allergies
💤 Sleep Habits
⏰ Aging Skin

What you need to do is figure out the cause. Try the pinch test 🤏 from the video.

If the culprit is thin skin (the darkness seems to disappear when you pull the skin up), you need a retinoid to increase collagen production and plump the skin. Look for one that’s safe for use around the eyes (oh, hello, @barefaced RetinAL Skin Therapy 👋). I recommend putting an eye cream on prior to a retinoid to prevent product migration into the eye area.

If the skin stays dark when raised, you need to work on brightening the pigmentation of the skin. Barefaced Brightening Duo (Liquid Gold + Brightening Serum) is formulated with kojic acid, arbutin, licorice, and vitamin C. Some of the best natural skin lighteners and brighteners available ! 🌟

What sunscreen to use on your kids?! I have gotten this question no less than a thousand times. So here we go:

Comment ‘SPF’ and I’ll send you the link to the sunscreens I’m using on my kids right now🌞

My kids are pretty picky about sunscreen and love to apply it themselves. I love an spf stick for this reason and they are easy for reapplication too!

The twins have more sensitive skin so I’ve been sticking with mustela brand or anything that is pure zinc. Zinc is an anti inflammatory too, which can be helpful for eczema prone skin.

Using a beauty blender for application is a hack I’ve seen when applying SPF on kids, my two cents with that form of application is making sure they are actually getting sufficient coverage.

The way I see it: our kids are wearing sunscreen so much more than we ever did so they are already ahead of the game. Surprisingly, I don’t obsess over it but just try to be mindful that they don’t get burned and reapply when they get out of the water. The more you burn, the greater your risk for skin cancer. Even just ONE blistering sunburn in childhood or teen years more than DOUBLES your chances of developing melanoma later in life. 🤯

We’ve been talking about the major benefits that glycolic acid + retinoids can have on the skin, so how do you use them together in your routine? 🤝

→ You always want to use stronger glycolic acid products, like Glow Peel Pads, a full day before retinoid usage. 📆 This allows the skin to be fully exfoliated, prepped, and ready for retinoid penetration. (Let’s say you start on Monday, you can use GPP in your AM routine or PM routine as preferred, but don’t use your retinoid until Tuesday PM.)

→ Toning Pads (II) are a more gentle product with a lower percentage of glycolic acid designed for daily or twice daily usage. So you can still use them in conjunction with retinoids daily as tolerated.

→ Follow the schedule: exfoliate, retinoid, retinoid, rest. Then repeat. As you start tolerating the retinoid more, feel free to skip the rest night. Research shows maximum retinoid results come when used 5-7x/week.

Did you know: 💭 Traditional sunscreens don’t protect against visible light?! 

They’re typically formulated to block invisible light—the UVA and UVB rays we’re always talking about around here. ☀️

However, if you’re still noticing lingering dark spots or new ones forming, the culprit could be visible light. This is the light the human eye can see, those colors of the 🌈, and according to a 2015 study by dermatologists, this type of light can definitely affect your skin’s pigment!

So, then what in the world is the solution?! 

A: Iron oxides! 🪨 These minerals, typically found in cosmetics + skincare for coloring purposes, also prevent your skin from the damaging effects of visible light.💡

That means, your best bet is a combo of traditional SPF and iron oxides. 🤝 Here’s where Tinted Protection SPF 50+ enters the chat!

This type of broad spectrum SPF protects against UV rays while it’s iron oxides intercept visible light. Bonus, the tint warms to the body’s temperature to blend into the skin and match a wide-range of skin tones! 🫶🏻🫶🏼🫶🏽🫶🏾🫶🏿

Month 1️⃣ — use your retinoid every 3rd night

Month 2️⃣ — use your retinoid every 2nd night

Month 3️⃣ — use your retinoid every night, or on alternating nights.

To minimize reactions that are common with initial usage—such as sensitivity, dryness, and irritation—try the Barefaced Method for gradually introducing new products into your routine:

→ Start using a new product 3 days/week on ALTERNATING days. 🗓

→ Adding more than one new product? Introduce the same way, just on different days.

→ Follow that schedule for 2️⃣ weeks.

→ If your skin feels balanced, hydrated, and healthy, with no sensitized reactions, you’re ready to up frequency by one day.

I have completely eliminated physical exfoliation from my routine on my face. I have rosacea-prone skin and found it to be too irritating. Ok let’s break down physical vs. chemical exfoliation...

🧽physical:
- granular scrubs, brushes, cloths, etc.
- mechnically scrape away dead skin cells
- recommended 1-2x a week, max
- can damage the skin barrier if too much pressure is applied

✨ chemical:
- a safer and gentler way to exfoliate and much less abrasive than physical; therefore, better tolerated especially if you have sensitive skin
- alpha-hydroxy and beta-hydroxy acids dissolve dead skin cells and decongest pores by gently loosening the bonds between them
- depending on formulation some, like @barefaced Toning Pads can be used up to 1-2x daily as tolerated (always introduce gradually)
- higher percentage of acids should be used less frequently, ie: our Glow Peel Pads should only be used 1-3x/wk on the face; on the body can be used daily

retinoids can get a bad rap but that’s probably because your not using the right one for your skin type. So many retinoids, like tretinoin and retinol cause sensitivity, dryness, irritation for many skin types, which leads to inconsistent usage. The best retinoid for your skin is the one you can tolerate daily without side effects. It’s ok to have some side effects when starting one but consistently causing irritation to the skin causes inflammation and we don’t want to be triggering a continual inflammatory response. 

We added calming, soothing ingredients to @barefaced RetinAL Skin Therapy to improve tolerability and reduce unwanted side effects. We also added Bakuchiol, which helps the skin to tolerate retinoids better and allows retinoids to work longer and more effectively on the skin 🤝
